From: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
Date: 2026-05-14
Subject: [PATCH] ps4_mts: v113 — hotswap-safe mts_remove() for module dev workflow

Pairs with the CONFIG_PS4_MTS=y → =m flip in config/6.x-baikal.config.
Together they enable the module-hotswap dev workflow: per-iteration
becomes ~30 seconds (rebuild .ko + scp + rmmod/insmod) instead of
~15 minutes (full reboot + PSFree-Enhanced jailbreak gauntlet).

Four-agent consensus (hermes + kimi + deepseek + glm, 2026-05-14):
if rmmod doesn't fully quiesce the hardware BEFORE freeing IRQ and
DMA resources, the Baikal southbridge can wedge into power-cycle
territory — defeating the whole speedup.  This patch adds the missing
quiesce steps to mts_remove():

  - wake_up_process(phy_ctrl_thread) before kthread_stop, so the
    thread can observe kthread_should_stop() and exit interruptible
    sleep (kimi caught this gap).

  - W1C clear of BAR+0x50 (IRQ_STATUS) AFTER masking IRQs, so no
    stale pending bit fires on the very first IRQ of the next insmod
    before our handlers are wired up (hermes).

Order of operations is now:

  1. unregister_netdev    (does netif_stop_queue + napi_disable
                           internally; kernel calls those on the
                           netdev's transition path)
  2. netif_napi_del       (frees NAPI poll state)
  3. wake + kthread_stop  (one kthread: phy_ctrl_thread)
  4. timer_delete_sync    (dbg_timer + link_poll — synchronous
                           wait, no callback can fire after)
  5. clear engine bit 0   (RX_KICK and TX_KICK — no new DMA work)
  6. disable IRQ block    (BAR+0x204 = 0)
  7. clear IRQ mask       (BAR+0x54 = 0)
  8. W1C status           (BAR+0x50 — clear any pending bit)
  9. free_irq             (must precede pci_free_irq_vectors)
 10. pci_free_irq_vectors

Glm's bonus suggestion (pci_reset_function for MSI vector release
on Baikal) is NOT added in this patch — kept as a fallback if the
first rmmod test reveals MSI vectors don't de-assert.  We'll test
the simpler version first.

Required for testing: CONFIG_PS4_MTS=m + this patch + kernel rebuild
that produces /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/kernel/drivers/net/ethernet/
sony/ps4_mts.ko.  Validation test (run ONCE on known-good source
before relying on hotswap):

  ssh ps4 'sudo ip link set enp0s20f1 down;
           sudo rmmod ps4_mts;
           lsmod | grep ps4_mts || echo CLEAN;
           grep ps4_mts /proc/interrupts || echo NO_STRAY_IRQ;
           sudo insmod /lib/modules/.../ps4_mts.ko;
           dmesg | tail -20'

If that round-trip survives without panic / wedge, the workflow is
unlocked.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
---
 drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c | 28 +++++++++++++++++++++++++---
 1 file changed, 25 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)

--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
@@ -2087,12 +2087,29 @@
 	struct net_device *ndev = pci_get_drvdata(pdev);
 	struct mts *mts = netdev_priv(ndev);

+	/*
+	 * v113: hotswap-safe remove.  Agents (hermes+kimi+deepseek+glm,
+	 * 2026-05-14) flagged that if any DMA engine or kthread fires
+	 * after rmmod has freed module text/rings, the southbridge can
+	 * wedge into power-cycle territory.  Order matters:
+	 *   1) unregister_netdev (which does netif_stop_queue + napi_disable)
+	 *   2) wake + stop kthreads (wake first so they can observe
+	 *      kthread_should_stop() and exit interruptible sleep)
+	 *   3) delete timers (synchronous — won't fire after this)
+	 *   4) stop RX/TX engines (so no new DMA completions)
+	 *   5) disable IRQ block (so no new MSIs)
+	 *   6) W1C any pending IRQ status (so no stale IRQ on next insmod)
+	 *   7) free_irq (must precede pci_free_irq_vectors)
+	 *   8) pci_free_irq_vectors
+	 */
 	if (mts->netdev_registered)
 		unregister_netdev(ndev);
 	netif_napi_del(&mts->napi);

-	if (mts->phy_ctrl_thread)
+	if (mts->phy_ctrl_thread) {
+		wake_up_process(mts->phy_ctrl_thread);
 		kthread_stop(mts->phy_ctrl_thread);
+	}
 	timer_delete_sync(&mts->dbg_timer);
 	timer_delete_sync(&mts->link_poll);

@@ -2104,6 +2121,11 @@

 	writel(0, mts->bar + MTS_IRQ_ENABLE_FULL);
 	writel(0, mts->bar + MTS_IRQ_MASK);
+	/* v113: W1C any pending IRQ status — otherwise a stale bit
+	 * could trigger the very first IRQ on the next insmod before
+	 * our handlers are wired up. */
+	writel(readl(mts->bar + MTS_IRQ_STATUS), mts->bar + MTS_IRQ_STATUS);
+	(void)readl(mts->bar + MTS_IRQ_STATUS);

 	if (mts->irq_registered) {
 		free_irq(mts->irq, mts);
